I don't really want to see this, but I have another project that needs funding. 

Gun does have some holster wear, it was in (and out) of a holster for 16 years) If the finish bugs you, you can have it bead blasted here in Houston for $179.00, and at my price, it will STILL be a steal.

The grip, since some ask, is original to the gun. 

The current ambi safety was added ages ago.

title: For Sale:  Rare Steyr model M 30-06, Double Set Triggers
postcontent:
This is a rare Steyr Model M chambered in 30-06. The rifle has had some use. There is a small chip on the tang, just behind the action, as well as one just underneath of the bolt handle. These are cosmetic only, and are not very sizeable. When I purchased this rifle, it had a crack along the side (from below the safety to the trigger guard). I took it upon myself to do a good job repairing it. As the stock is made of ABS, I made a bonding agent from the same type of material and repaired the crack.

Because the material I used to repair the crack is the same type as the stock is made of, it is essentially like the stock has been welded back together. When the same material is used to repair a crack as is around it, the resulting bond is extremely strong. The crack was located in a region of the stock that is not highly stressed, and combine this with the high strength of this repair, it is essentially as strong as it was when new. To assure that the repair matches the stock’s color as closely as possible, I used a stain. With the stain and bonding agent being of similar color to the original stock, the repair is not all that noticeable. To minimize the visibility of the repair, I attempted to replicate the existing checkering on the bond. I can attest to the strength of the repair, as I put 15 rounds through it shortly after bonding it together. The bond held perfectly.

Besides the now-repaired crack, this rifle is in good condition. The bolt is remarkably smooth; it feels like it is running on ball bearings. When I shot this rifle, it was very accurate. This rifle has a very similar bolt design to the SSG-69, so it is capable of outstanding accuracy when in good hands. If you have any questions about this Steyr, please contact me.

The rifle weighs about 7.25 pounds without the scope and balances very well. It points intuitively and will make a great hunting rifle in a time-proven, effective cartridge.

It has a 23.622 inch cold hammer forged barrel (600 mm).
The barrel is free-floating.
This rifle is set in the Cycolac synthetic stock.
Has the standard parkerized finish.
The stock and finish are really nice features for hunting.

Cycolac synthetic stock; The stock has nice checkering on it to ensure a good grip even when wet, while maintaining a more traditional appearance than the typical synthetic stock. Also, being a synthetic stock, it is resistant to warping and is more stable in wet and high temperature conditions than wood.
The Steyr model M never sold all that well in this country, and it seems that virtually all of the ones available here come with a standard single trigger. This one has double set triggers. You have two modes in which to shoot. If you are at the range and desire an extremely light pull, you pull the rear trigger first. Pulling the rear trigger sets the front trigger to a very light weight, allowing you to be more accurate at the range. However, a very light pull weight can be hazardous when hunting. With double set triggers, you don't have to worry about a hair trigger. When hunting, you can simply pull the front trigger and have a normal trigger pull. The double set triggers allows you to have the best of both worlds; a hair trigger for target shooting at the range and a normal (good) trigger pull when hunting.

Some additional features of this rifle include

Has a rare set of quick-detachable scope mounts and rings. These mounts allow convenient and nearly instantaneous removal of the scope for ease of cleaning the rifle from the breech. Please note, the scope is not included with the rifle for this price. It has a Nikon Prostaff 3-9x40mm BDC that can be included for an additional $199 above the rifle’s auction price.
To return the rifle to a ready-to-fire state, the mounts come off as quickly as they came off. Once back on the rifle, the scope is typically very close (if not exactly) at your previous zero point. These mounts and rings are worth about $200 and are very difficult to find.
Most Steyr Model M’s that I have seen for sale have prices in the $1100-$1200 range. In light of the repaired crack, I have reduced the price of this rifle to be competitive. This repair is as strong as possible, and does not affect the safe functioning of the rifle. But, it seemed fair to decrease the price to make it competitive.

Please contact me for a shipping quote. I will charge you the exact amount that it costs me to ship (with insurance). I am an individual, without an FFL. So, if your FFL will not receive from a non-FFL holder, add $45 to the purchase price of this rifle so that I can go through my FFL.

I have many more pictures, just let me know if you would like more.

SOLD

Zeiss Conquest 3-12x56 8 Riflescope REDACTED

Conquest Scopes 3-12x56 ManualConquest Scopes 3-12x56 Manual
Key Features

* Zeiss Conquest Riflescope
Zeiss Conquest riflescopes are designed to meet the needs of North American hunters with an excellent price to performance ratio. They feature fully multicoated optics, waterproof construction, and 1/4 MOA precision adjustments.

* Hunting Turrets
Low profile hunting turrets with 1/4 MOA clicks, and turret caps

A bump up in power from the 2.5-10x, the 3-12x magnification range brings you in closer to more distant targets easily. The #8 reticle features four heavy posts and fine cross hairs. This configuration stands out well against dense brush and heavy cover. The four posts lead your eye to the center of the sight picture while the cross hairs establish your exact point of aim without obscuring the field of view.
First focal plane positioning of the reticle maintains its subtension across the magnification range. This enables accurate distance ranging and hold-over calculation.

postcontent:
Brand new suppressor-ready / tunable .300 Blackout Seekins Precision upper for any AR15 pistol or SBR, with 10" Seekins MCSR V2 Keymod rail and Seekins adjustable gas block. This is a high quality factory upper professionally built by Seekins Precision. The 10.5" barrel is Black Nitride / melonite treated which is more accurate and lasts longer than chrome lined. The extremely lightweight 10" MCSR V2 Keymod rail has a 1.8" inside diameter to accommodate suppressors. The Seekins adjustable gas block is over $60 alone and offers you complete tuning capabilities (see below).

http://www.seekinsprecision.com/m16-bolt-carrier-group.html

From the manufacturer:
The Seekins Precision Adjustable Gas Block lets you to fine tune your rifle's gas system for smoother cycling and operation. Regulating the amount of gas used to cycle the action allows tuning the rifle’s operation to a specific load and the use of low mass bolt carriers, buffers and springs to reduce felt recoil. This is critical to allow faster follow up shots, target acquisition and reliability.
The Seekins Precision Adjustable Gas Block is field adjustable. Operation is easy, simply turn the gas regulating screw in to lessen the amount of gas and out to add more gas, then use the brass set screw to lock the setting in place. The overall height of the gas block is 1.37” with left to right dimensions at .94” to fit under most hand guards and still have the customization of an adjustable gas block.
Melonite Coated to reduce wear and corrosion for extended periods of fire, it also makes cleaning easier, as carbon build up will not adhere to the non-reflective coated surface as much as it does on standard Parkerized finishes.

The MCSR V2 rail is comfortable, extremely light weight modular rail system that will work in any situation as well as comfortably fit a suppressor inside the rail. The MCSR V2 was designed to make using a quick mounted suppressor easy to install or remove while inside the rail.
The MCSR V2 rail is designed so that the 3, 6, and 9 o'clock positions will accept all keymod accessories and have two anti-rotation QD positions per side (6total). The internal dimension has increased to 1.8" to accommodate most suppressors on the market.

title: For Sale/Trade:  RARE 1943 COLT M1911 A1 National Match
postcontent:
RARE Colt M1911 A1 early model national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped to Springfield Armory in February of 1943. It was Issued to an enlisted serviceman at the time. (Trying to find out who it was issued to now through different channels.) There are specific clues on the gun that tell you who it MIGHT have gone to.. There is AA inscribed (Not stamped) on the ivory grips and on the frame Next to GHD. GHD is significant because Col. Guy H. Drewry inspected ordnance from June 17, 1942 to July 15, 1945 For COLT.

After having multiple collectors and Colt dealers at the gun show look at it. "AA" is believed to stand for "All American" 82nd Airborne. Which would match the dates the gun was issued, and the eagle carved on the Ivory grips. 82 Airborne was the first Airborne division in US Army history and had three major drops, made their first drop in July of 1943 to invade Sicily. Second was Salerno on 13 September 1943. The third was the invasion of Normandy Jun 1944.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. But not all pistols back then were stamped with "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted national match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by a gunsmith. At some point it was re-blued, and fixtures were 24k gold plated and Ivory grips added. It has been determined the gold was added many many years ago as some has worn off in spots. Bluing and finish is still very nice... Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. I have put 100 rounds through it and drives tacks. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. 4,500$ cash obo.. All reasonable offers considered. Email if interested. Will trade multiple guns.. Please list your offer and values of guns. email or text 918-four02-zero854.
